Behavioral differences worth flagging with comments (can't auto-fix safely):

Issue                                                                                               Risk
NULL ordering: Impala defaults NULLS FIRST, Trino defaults NULLS LAST                               Silent row reordering
CAST() returns NULL on failure in Impala; throws error in Trino (TRY_CAST is the safe equivalent)   Runtime errors on bad data
Integer division: Trino 7/2 = 3, Impala may return 3.5                                              Silent wrong results
Decimal arithmetic exceeding precision 38 throws in Trino, truncates in Impala                      Runtime errors or wrong results






Conclusion

The Impala/Hive to Trino/Presto migration landscape has mature tooling for syntax conversion but immature solutions for semantic equivalence validation. sqlglot is the clear first choice for automated transpilation, GitHub handling the Hive→Trino/Presto path well but requiring Hive-dialect proxying for Impala sources. LinkedIn Coral fills the gap for semantically complex Hive view translation Libraries.ioTrino but handles only SELECT queries. GitHub The Oracle BDS bash script remains the only comprehensive Impala-specific conversion resource. Oracleoracle

The most important insight from practitioner experience is that the migration risk is inversely proportional to error visibility: explicit syntax errors from unsupported functions are easily caught, but silent behavioral differences in NULL ordering, decimal arithmetic, integer division, and timestamp semantics corrupt data without alerting anyone. Production migrations should therefore prioritize building automated result-comparison infrastructure over perfecting SQL conversion tooling. Every company that shared their experience—from Lyft's 250K daily queries Trino to LY Corp's 300+ pipelines— lycorpconverged on the same conclusion: parallel execution with row-level validation is not optional.
